english:
  title: Memorial on Current State Affairs
  author: Jo Jun
  language: eng
  text: "I respectfully examine the record: In the Zhou Rites, the Grand Precept of the Celestial Ministry, held by one Minister, oversees the Six Exemplars to assist the King in governing the realm. Those below the Minister of Personnel each attend to their assigned duties. The six ministers comprise three hundred sixty subordinate offices, all unified under these six ministers, who in turn are unified under the Grand Precept. Though official ranks and titles change with successive ages, the fundamental principle never departs from these six ministries.\n\nWhen our Great Founder established the dynasty, he instituted offices and divided responsibilities, appointing Chancellor to oversee the Six Ministries, and placing Inspectors and Temples and Treasuries to support them. This was indeed an excellent system. Yet as law became antiquated, disorders arose: those managing registrations know not how to recommend merit, so the flow of talent became corrupted; those handling military rolls know not the true strength of forces, so military readiness declined. When household registrations wax and wane, when wealth increases and diminishes, when litigation lacks order, when bandits go unchecked—those charged with managing land and laws remain utterly ignorant of their duties. Can the officials of Rites truly conduct their affairs? Can the officials of Works truly fulfill their roles? The Six Ministries are the foundation of all offices and the source of all governance. When the foundation is disordered, the branches cannot be ordered.\n\nNow the hundred officials and various bureaus stand scattered without hierarchy, neglecting their responsibilities, their names alone surviving while their substance has perished. Though ruler and minister labor with anxiety, the conduct of affairs becomes difficult.\n\nWe humbly propose that the affairs of the Six Exemplars be returned to the Six Ministries, with each bureau properly assigned to one of them. The Chancellor and those below the Attendant-in-Waiting should in turn deliberate on bureau matters. The密直 should in turn concurrently serve as Minister, drawing together the governing threads above, with the Protector serving as Minister of each of the Six Ministries, overseeing all clerks and subordinate bureaus. Each should heed commands according to their duty below. Major matters shall be handled by the ministry clerks; minor matters by the six categories of officials. Thus shall the simple constrain the complex, the lower obey the superior, the upper and lower sustain one another, the great and small be unified—as when pulling the mesh draws the net's knots tight, as when the collar is seized the robe follows. The ruler and minister may rest at ease above while the hundred offices labor below, making edicts easy to implement and governance easy to conduct.\n\nThe ruler's duty is but to deliberate with his minister; the minister's duty is but to advance worthy men and reject small men, thereby correcting the hundred officials. When the minister's seat is filled by capable men, all under heaven finds order—how much more a single realm!\n\nZhou Gong, Shao Gong, and the Duke of Zhou were ministers to Kings Wen, Wu, Cheng, and Kang; Xiao He and Cao Can were ministers to the Han founder; Fang Xuanling and Du Ruhui were ministers to Tang Taizong.\n\nIn our dynasty's system, the Ministry of Personnel has the posts of Minister, Attendant-in-Waiting, Concurrent Ministers, Vice Ministers, and Political Councillors—five ranks mirroring the Five Stars of Heaven. The Seven of the Privy Council mirror the Big Dipper. When Chancellor and Privy Councillor began sitting together at the dynasty's founding, it was a practice from Yuan times. In recent ages, those sitting in the Grand Hall and participating in state affairs have numbered sixty or seventy—an excess of offices unseen in antiquity.\n\nHenceforth, we request that only those who discourse on the Way, plan for the realm, balance yin and yang, and rectify themselves to rectify all officials; only those who are clean and loyal, hate corruption and love worthy men, and regard the state as themselves—be granted the two offices. Henceforth, not those who conquer in battle, seize in siege, stand foremost in valor, or inspire awe among distant peoples. \n\nThe Han's Guangwu Emperor, despite all-under-heaven's vastness and the riches of the Four Seas, reduced officials to but one-tenth, thereby achieving the restoration to order. All unnecessary offices and useless positions should be entirely eliminated, restoring the constitution of our ancestors who established offices in Heaven's stead, thereby demonstrating the renewal that befits our enlightened court.\n\nThe Six Temples and Seven Inspectorates originally had no directors. Recently they have added ranks of Examining Censor and Protector, yet these officials neither attend to their duties nor visit their offices, wasting heaven's stipends while leaving posts vacant. Henceforth, those promoted to these ranks should, if capable, have their rank lowered to assume their actual duties. Those newly appointed should not be granted these ranks.\n\nThe Spring and Autumn records: \"Heaven's King sent the son of Rengshu to visit.\" The Master thereby mourned that the Zhou house, through family favoritism, placed immature and weak youths in office, wasting Heaven's stipends while neglecting Heaven's work.\n\nDuring our Cultured Sage's thirty-eight years of rule, such was the flourishing of peace because all he employed were seasoned men. Henceforth, the young and weak children of dukes, ministers, and great officers shall not receive positions of the ninth rank or above in the Eastern Ranks. Should any fraudulently receive such posts, their fathers and elder brothers shall be held accountable.\n\nThe Censorate, serving as the ruler's eyes and ears, inspects all officials, examining both sacrifices and court audiences down to the receipt and disbursement of funds. Though their rank be low, their responsibility is heavy. We request that henceforth the Censorate recommend candidates for these posts, with rank elevated to the next step above, thereby strengthening the administration.\n\nThe provincial governor is a post nearest to the people and cannot be considered lightly. Yet among those recently appointed, some are unknown to the scholarly world. Henceforth, only those who have held prominent posts with established reputation, or who have served in various provinces and demonstrated proven accomplishment, shall be appointed. All hunting expeditions and banquets shall be entirely prohibited.\n\nThe County Inspector and County Magistrate are likewise posts near the people. Yet in recent times, as official paths have multiplied, men have deemed these positions shameful. Thus illiterate scribes and clerks of little learning have been employed, bringing harm to the people. Henceforth, let the Censorate and Six Ministries recommend capable individuals, who shall be elevated to participate in administration to enhance the importance of their posts. Let all stabilizing positions be entirely abolished. Those scribes and clerks shall hold only provisional posts. As for public and private slaves, local magistrates' aides, and merchants of base origin who fraudulently hold office, we request permission for the Censorate to strip all such persons of their posts regardless of rank.\n\nThe Bureau of Post-Stations, which supervises the eight provinces' relay stations, has in recent years abandoned its official hall to operate from private homes. Written dispatches are sent and documents processed through the intercession of powerful families and friends, with riders and postal clerks departing in endless succession. The relay station personnel have grown scarce and depleted. Henceforth, let the Bureau of Post-Stations be subordinated to the Military Registry. All horses and relay personnel shall be dispatched only upon written order from the Grand Hall.\n\nThe Ministry of Royal Steeds manages the horses of the royal conveyance, corresponding to the Duke of Buo's office in Zhou times. Selection for posts near the royal person requires utmost care. Yet in recent times, Inner Mounted Attendants and Inner Palace Servants have monopolized these duties, recently committing outrages. When gathering fodder, they employ countless extortions. When transporting supplies into the city, draft oxen sicken and collapse, devastation spreading through the capital districts and radiating to the provinces. A single province's tax grain now costs nearly nine hundred bolts of cloth to procure; this is uniform across all provinces. Moreover, they conscript tax households, calling them \"driver personnel,\" numbering in the hundreds, placing them outside official registers, establishing private estates and using them like slaves. The harm to the people and the state is truly lamentable.\n\nHenceforth, let the Ministry of Mounted Attendants be subordinated to the Ministry of Royal Steeds. Inner servants shall not be appointed. Let carefully selected honest and capable individuals assume these positions, rotating daily on duty. Let them personally measure and distribute all fodder and grain. For the capital region's fodder, determine quantities according to horses needed and distribute monthly. Moreover, let the Censorate conduct inspections. For each rotation, place five veterinarians and thirty driver personnel; all others shall be eliminated and subordinated to the Bureau of Militia.\n\nIt is the established rule that the Construction Bureau exists when needed and is abolished when not. The Bureau of Palace Construction was originally established for construction work, later inheriting the role of maintenance. It manages all timber and metal used throughout the realm, sending officials and exhausting relay resources, depleting the people's wealth and consuming their strength. A single tree's hauling kills ten oxen; a single furnace's operation exhausts ten farmers; a single bundle of hemp or handful of vine waste ten bolts of cloth. When taking from the people, they flay skin and crush bone; when spending on private use, they treat it like mud and sand.\n\nLet the Construction Bureau be abolished and subordinated to the Ministry of Maintenance. Similarly, let the Fire Defense and Fire Bucket bureaus be abolished and subordinated to the Military Weapons Ministry. Let only the cleanest and most upright be selected to serve, with Censorate supervision. Let the timber and tiles from the palace and property seized from criminals, materials from the Two Rivers and various kilns, all be directed toward construction projects. All timber cutting and tile making shall be suspended for three years to give the people rest.\n\nThe capital is the realm's foundation and where civilization first manifests. Its people exist solely to defend the royal household. Yet in recent times, education lacks system, deception has become habit, forced labor grows burdensome, and conditions daily decline. Let the Bureau of Capital Affairs be abolished. Let the five districts be subordinated to the Kaesong Garrison. For each ward, select esteemed elders of learning as ward chiefs, educate the youth according to established methods, and ensure that base persons and merchants' children each apply themselves to their professions, not gathering to play in the streets and fostering frivolous customs. Those who violate shall be held accountable along with their fathers and elder brothers. Let the Central Ministry's palace bureaus, storehouses, and slaves, as well as recently confiscated slaves from exiled persons' estates, be inventoried by the Adjudication Bureau according to their numbers, ensuring no omissions. When construction projects or provisions for guests and religious services arise, employ them in such work. Exempt them entirely from the miscellaneous labor of wards and thereby give them peace and enable them to defend the royal household.\n\nLi Renym monopolized authority for over twenty years, his crimes accumulated and his evils reached their limit. Fortunately, Heaven has taken him. Strip away his ranks and refuse him honorific epitaph, thereby cautioning those who do wrong.\n\nThe Pure and Steadfast Duke Gyeong Bokhung guarded his honor through integrity but was driven out by Renym's faction and died in exile. Grant him an imperial letter and conduct sacrifice at his tomb.\n\nAttendant-in-Waiting Yi Jasong was honest and principled, dying without just cause. The people of the realm deeply lament this. Grant him honorific epitaph and generously sustain his household.\n\nOur ancestors' robes, caps, and rites and music all followed Tang customs. When the Yuan appeared, they were suppressed by the Barbarian Khan's system, and we abandoned the Middle Kingdom's ways to follow the nomads, making it impossible to distinguish upper from lower or settle the people's minds. Our Hyeonjong, indignant at this loss of hierarchy, resolved to transform barbarians through the Middle Kingdom's ways, recovering the grandeur of our ancestors. He sent representations to the Yuan requesting to change from barbarian dress. But soon he passed away. The Regent King took up his intention and achieved the request, though it was altered by executing officials midway. Since Your Highness ascended, you have personally worn civilized dress, and together with officials and people, we began anew. Yet some still resist the proper ranks, impeding the policy of renewal.\n\nLet the Censorate establish a date and promulgate law. All who refuse shall be held accountable.\n\nIn recent years, as treacherous officials have succeeded one another in power, bribes have determined rank and favor has determined death and life. The way of scholars has transformed—all rush to the doors of the powerful day and night, leaving their heaven-given duties vacant. Let the competent bureaus have each day's litigation and judgment cases brought before the Two Offices, with each bureau sitting in its own hall daily to conduct affairs. Those who rush to power's gates neglecting their duties shall have their posts suspended and salaries seized.\n\nSince criminal law lacks fixed standards, internal and external officials operate arbitrarily. Now the positions of legal editor are all held by literary men with no other duties. Let them be tasked with revising and codifying the criminal code to benefit ten thousand generations. Similarly, let them revise and promulgate the protocols between internal and external palaces and the formats for official communications.\n\nIn antiquity, customs were pure and deception did not arise, so official resignations were countersigned by the officials of the grand hall. As the age has declined and deception has spread, recently those from the rank of Senior General downward have had their seals applied by the Military Registry, and those from Protector-rank downward by the Administration Bureau, to prevent fraud. Now when the Grand Council issues documents to internal and external offices concerning disbursement of funds, execution of persons, dispensing of authority, and issuance of commands—matters of utmost gravity—only a single recorder's signature appears. This is not a proper means of detecting fraud.\n\nLet us follow the precedent of court resignations and have all Grand Hall documents sealed with the official stamp. \n\nThe old system required that when imperial commands regarding storehouses and palaces were issued, they be sealed with the seal of credence. Now only Inner Servants sign them, which again fails to prevent fraud. For all internal supplies, let the Grand Council provide them without issuing imperial commands, thereby closing the source of Inner Servant thefts.\n\nWhen great officers and their households communicate privately with officials handling litigation and finance, they overturn right and wrong and pilfer official property, with abuses multiplying. We request that all such be prohibited. Those who violate, whether petitioner or recipient, shall be charged with lack of integrity. Similarly, let each bureau prohibit soldiers' personal requests and gifts from external officials entirely. Those who violate shall likewise be charged with lack of integrity.\n\nIn antiquity, men became commoners at sixteen and began state service, and at sixty became elders and were exempted. Each year, provincial governments would count households by name and report to Inspecting Censors, who would report to the Ministry of Revenue, so the court could conscript and conscript labor as easily as pointing. Recently this system collapsed. Governors know not their province's households; Censors know not a region's households. When conscription comes, local clerks practice deception for bribes—the wealthy and strong are exempted while the poor and weak are conscripted. Unable to bear the burden, they flee, whereupon the wealthy and strong take their place until they too become poor and flee.\n\nThose tasked with conscription, angered by the clerks' deception, apply cruel torments—cutting ears and slitting noses. The clerks too flee under this suffering. Clerks and common people scatter fleeing—empty provinces result from unregistered households.\n\nLet us now conduct a land survey, examining what land each household cultivates. Based on land quantity, classify households as upper, middle, or lower grades. Distinguish between common and base categories. Have governors report to Inspecting Censors, who report to the Ministry of Revenue. Thus the court has records for conscription and labor assignment, sending them out in timely fashion. Should governors or Censors violate these orders, they shall immediately face punishment.\n\nThe fish-salting, livestock-breeding abundance of the various provinces is indispensable to the state. When our Sage had not yet unified Silla and Baekje, he first organized the water army, personally piloted the tower-ships downstream from Keum Fortress and took possession. Thus the profits of the islands all belonged to the state, providing resources to unify the Three Han. South of the Yalu River lies mostly mountains, yet fertile fields lie along the coasts—thousands of li of rich lands now lost to the Japanese pirates while reeds stretch to heaven.\n\nHaving lost both the profits of fish-salt and livestock-breeding and the income of fertile fields, let us follow the Han precedent of recruiting people to settle frontier wastelands to defend against the Xiongnu. Those who open wasteland in abandoned districts shall be exempted from tax for twenty years and shall not be conscripted. Place them entirely under the Water Army Command, strengthening fortifications, gathering the elderly and weak, establishing distant outposts, and carefully maintaining beacon-fires. During times of peace, let them cultivate fields, manage salt production, and conduct metalwork for livelihood, while building warships in season. When raiders come, clear the fields, enter the fortifications, and let the water army strike. From Hap'o to Uiju, establish this everywhere. Within years, fled people shall return to their homes, border regions shall fill, numerous warships shall be built, water forces shall gain experience, sea pirates shall flee, borders shall be secure, transport shall flow freely, granaries shall fill.\n\nFor commanders of water armies and regional generals who can establish garrison farms, repair warships, win the people's hearts, issue orders, destroy bandits, and secure the borders—grant them island-lands to enjoy income across generations, transmitting to heirs. Those who lose fortifications or provinces shall face military law without mercy, demonstrating reward and punishment.\n\nJeolla, Gyeongsang, and Yangguang provinces produce taxes and tributes and form the state's heart. Now Japanese pirates rampage, attacking and seizing our provinces, trampling our crops, slaughtering our elderly and weak, enslaving our able-bodied men. Yet those commanding armies crouch within walls, showing no will to fight. Enemy strength grows daily. We request a major military campaign be launched to sweep them clean in timely fashion.\n\nThe northwest frontier forms the state's protective screen. Recently, treacherous officials usurped power and widely placed their private followers. Regional generals and commanders now exceed established numbers, creating unsustainable provincial burdens, forcing the people to flee. Henceforth, select individuals combining military and civil capabilities with long-established authority—place one regional general per province with two vice-commanders, eliminating all others.\n\nMerchants flock to powerful families seeking thousand-commander posts, exploiting and crushing the people without limit. Henceforth, let each region's general select those whose authority and benevolence win the people's trust for appointment, and do not rotate them frequently.\n\nPowerful families compete in trade, collecting furs, pine seeds, ginseng, honey, beeswax, rice, and beans from the people, causing severe suffering. With elderly and children in hand, people cross the river heading west—truly a matter for bitter tears. Henceforth, entirely prohibit such purchasing. Those who violate shall face stringent punishment.\n\nFrom prior times, goods seized from condemned corrupt officials remain partially uncollected among the people. Let these be inventoried for official use. Prohibit entirely the forced gifts of hawks, falcons, and furs.\n\nHouseholders and miscellaneous laborers who do not engage in agriculture yet consume the people's harvest lack stable property and thus stable character. Gathering in mountain valleys, they falsely claim to be Japanese pirates—their strength is formidable and requires early action. Henceforth, have provincial authorities register their population and record them permanently to prevent wandering. Grant them vacant lands to encourage farming. Let them dwell alongside common people. Those who violate shall face legal punishment from the authorities."
  footnotes:
    - 成衆愛馬 (seong jung ae ma) refers to garrison soldiers who protected the capital and transported supplies; their service was essential to national defense.
    - The Six Ministries (육부) - Personnel, Revenue, Rites, War, Justice, and Works - form the traditional administrative structure inherited from Chinese bureaucratic traditions.
    - The reference to the Spring and Autumn Annals concerns improper appointment of unqualified relatives to office, a cautionary precedent against nepotism.
